00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:20.840
&gt;&gt; Sarah Tomlinson: From
October 1939 to April 1940,

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:24.570
Alan Lomax began his first
radio series of many,

00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:29.410
when he hosted 25 Folk Music
of America radio broadcasts,

00:07:29.410 --> 00:07:33.280
for the CBS American
School of the Air.

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:40.240
These broadcasts listened
to during a school day,

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:44.430
by students in upper grades and
high school, included a wide array

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:48.050
of folk music from sea shanties
to children's songs of play.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:53.540
Lomax and his collaborators, also
prioritized musical diversity

00:07:53.540 --> 00:07:57.620 position:56%
as they featured works by women
composers like Ruth Crawford Seeger,

00:07:57.620 --> 00:08:00.900
African American performers like
Huddie "Lead Belly" Ledbetter,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:06.220
and broadcast themes such as
poor farmer songs and hobo songs.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:09.550 position:56%
As folk music scholar Rachel
Donaldson has argued, the Folk Music

00:08:09.550 --> 00:08:14.040 position:56%
of America broadcasts, show Lomax's
early concern for multi-culturalism.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:17.980
And throughout the week,
my work-a-thon colleagues

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:22.290
and I have also discussed how
this manifested in Lomax's idea

00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:27.170
of cultural equity, a phrase
that he coins later in life.

00:08:27.170 --> 00:08:30.680
Lomax's early engagement with
many different styles of music

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:34.920
and identities of people, also
extended to his audiences.

00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:37.850
Looking to the Folklife
Center's rich body of material

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:42.060
on the Folk Music of America
broadcasts, we can see

00:08:42.060 --> 00:08:45.190
and hear how Lomax engaged
with radio listeners

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:49.760 position:56%
in multi-faceted ways, such as
through fan mail, classroom manuals,

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:53.260
singalongs, and song collecting.

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:58.060
We can begin tracing Lomax's
engagement with radio listeners

00:08:58.060 --> 00:09:01.080
by looking to one of
the many fan letters

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:05.070
in the Alan Lomax CBS
Radio Series Collection.

00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:08.380
In 1940, Bill Damon [phonetic],

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:12.200 position:56%
a member of Mrs. Seegle's [phonetic]
class at the Stratford Ave. School

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:16.890
in Garden City, New York,
wrote to Alan Lomax.

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:19.510
"We have been listening to
your radio programs ever

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:21.790
since the first of the year.

00:09:21.790 --> 00:09:25.350
We have enjoyed them very much, but
we have a few criticisms to make."

00:09:25.350 --> 00:09:30.260
And to two of these
criticisms first.

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:33.190
"The Negro Quartet
on Tuesday the 13th,

00:09:33.190 --> 00:09:36.720
the Negroes clapped their hands
so loud that it was very hard

00:09:36.720 --> 00:09:39.350
to understand the words."

00:09:39.350 --> 00:09:42.260
And second, "It would
be a lot better

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:44.700
if the programs were not changed."

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:48.560
And then he wrote under,
"What We Enjoyed,"

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:50.860
"These programs give
us a wider vocabulary

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:54.160
of different types and
some of the songs."

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:57.880
The grammar there in
school child [inaudible].

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:02.220
So, this one letter written by
young Bill, came in with a stack

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:05.650
of other letters, all by
students in Mrs. Seegle's class.

00:10:05.650 --> 00:10:10.670 position:56%
And so, she had each student write
to Lomax with criticisms and praises

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:15.090
about broadcasts that aired in
January and February of 1940.

00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:20.530
Bill references the broadcast that
the class listened to the same day

00:10:20.530 --> 00:10:22.360
that they wrote their letters.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:25.640
The broadcast was Negro
Folksongs, featuring spirituals,

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:30.020
and aired on February 13th, 1940.

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:34.620 position:56%
His complaint that the programs had
changed, refers to a schedule change

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:38.070
from the originally planned
program for February 13th,

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:42.360
which would have been British
Ballads in America, a Part II.

00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:44.940
Indeed, several of his peers
made similar complaints,

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:47.790
not only about the schedule change,

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:52.110
but also about the
quartets vocal clarity.

00:10:52.110 --> 00:10:55.700
The quartet was the
famous Golden Gate Quarter

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:58.970
of African American singers
from Charlotte, North Carolina.

00:10:58.970 --> 00:11:01.450
And the students' common
grievances hinted

00:11:01.450 --> 00:11:05.630
that there had been a class
discussion about the Folk Music

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:08.880
of America broadcast,
showing another manifestation

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:13.310
of listener engagement, and through
these letters, we can imagine what

00:11:13.310 --> 00:11:17.030
that class discussion
must have been like.

00:11:17.030 --> 00:11:20.490
While Mrs. Seegle did not
send a letter herself,

00:11:20.490 --> 00:11:21.960
her students' words revealed

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.320
that she may have had some
racialized notions that musicality

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.230
of the African American musical
styles and musicians are difficult

00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:33.720
to understand, in addition to her
preference for schedule regularity.

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:38.290
To Mrs. Seegle's credit, the
February 13th broadcast did depart

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:42.580
from an important tool for listener
engagement: The American School

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:45.530
of the Air teacher
and student manuals.

00:11:45.530 --> 00:11:49.720
Schoolrooms used these guides
to prepare for and follow along

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:51.050
with the radio broadcast.

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:55.540
On Folk Music of America, Lomax
specifically designed them

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.560
to facilitate singalongs.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.080
To prepare for the Negro Spirituals
program originally scheduled

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:05.010
for February 6th, the
manual instructed students

00:12:05.010 --> 00:12:07.830
to learn the chorus of
the folk song, "Samson."

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:11.590
And when the program did
air on February 13thm,

00:12:11.590 --> 00:12:15.070
Lomax invited students to
sing along as they listened.

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:18.180
And so, in the spirit
of audience engagement,

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:19.670
I invite us all to do the same.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:24.460
So, first what we'll do is, I'll
sing and we're actually only going

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:28.630
to learn half the chorus,
the first half.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:31.090
So, we'll do as --
I'll call in response,

00:12:31.090 --> 00:12:35.330
and then I'll play the broadcast
and you can sing along with that.

00:12:35.330 --> 00:12:38.510
And so, if Lawrence could
give me an [singing].

00:12:38.510 --> 00:13:01.530
[ Singing ]

00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:03.820
And now, we'll -- oh, one cue is

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:09.110
that you will hear the
quartet sing the chorus.

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:10.580
That's so that you can remember it.

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:13.750
And on the second time,
Lomax will say --

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:16.040
he'll say, "And everyone
in on the choruses,"

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:18.370
and that's the time
that you'll sing.

00:13:18.370 --> 00:13:20.210
So, wait until you
hear him say that.

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:21.890
And I'll cue you too.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:26.510
Okay, you can play the audio.

00:13:26.510 --> 00:15:16.050
[ Inaudible audio ]

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:17.350
Excellent.

00:15:17.350 --> 00:15:21.510
Thank you for -- I think we
