00:18:06.610 --> 00:18:11.280
The collection and
dissemination of traditional music,

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:14.100 position:56%
has often had a political dimension.

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:17.910
Folk music has frequently been
coopted into nationalistic projects

00:18:17.910 --> 00:18:21.190
in the context of conflict,
often propagating

00:18:21.190 --> 00:18:24.190
or constructing an
idealized national identity,

00:18:24.190 --> 00:18:27.460
which in many cases was based
on the perception that a soul

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:31.420
of a nation is reflected
in its rote culture.

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:33.360
This was particularly
important in the context

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:36.860
of Alan Lomax's radio work
during the Second World War,

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:38.930
during which time, he
was involved in a number

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:42.490
of groundbreaking radio programs,
both in the U.S. and the U.K.

00:18:42.490 --> 00:18:46.190
And due to his institutional
and professional connections,

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:51.110
Lomax was in a unique position at
this important historical juncture.

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:55.800
However, Lomax recognized that
folk song was not only as the voice

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:59.150
of the people, but as
the voice of the peoples.

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:02.680
Rather than promoting a monolithic
vision of an American identity

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:06.430
and culture, he was at pains
to emphasize the plurality

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:10.170
and the diversity of people
and culture within the nation.

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:12.250
This was born out in the
two projects that I'd

00:19:12.250 --> 00:19:16.710
like to talk about: The Radio
Research Project of 1941 to '42,

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:19.970
and the broadcast series giving
the title inspiration for this work

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:22.740
from Trans-Atlantic
Call: People to People.

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:26.860
So, at the outset of World War II,

00:19:26.860 --> 00:19:29.500
Lomax was already an
established ratio broadcaster

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:32.820
and folk music collector, here
at the Library of Congress.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:37.050
And in 1941, he was transferred
from the library to the U.S. Office

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:40.360
of War Information, which
was a government agency,

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.190
created to disseminate
information on both domestic

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:48.240 position:56%
and overseas fronts, but also to
build morale in the American public.

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:51.060
And from there, he became involved
in the Radio Research Project,

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:53.860
which was funded by the
Rockefeller Foundation,

00:19:53.860 --> 00:19:55.400
and developed by the
Library of Congress,

00:19:55.400 --> 00:20:00.020
Dr. Archibald MacLeish at the time.

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:04.180
Lomax's writings of this period,
showed that he considered folklore

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:07.010
and its process of communal
generation selection

00:20:07.010 --> 00:20:10.670
and development, to be a
democratic process in itself,

00:20:10.670 --> 00:20:14.200 position:56%
but he was also conscious that this
was true of the many varied regional

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:16.040
and immigrant communities
within the U.S.

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:20.950
During the war, the library's
activities had to be contextualized

00:20:20.950 --> 00:20:23.300
by their contribution
to the war effort,

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:26.320
and Lomax wrote several
proposals relating to the use

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:29.930
of folklife material, gathered
by the institution, exploring

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:33.480
and articulating the role of the
Archive of American Folk Song,

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:35.690
in the National Defense Program.

00:20:35.690 --> 00:20:40.670
He identified the problem
faced by America, thus.

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:44.790
He wrote, "Well in advance of any
armed aggression against a state,

00:20:44.790 --> 00:20:48.670
fascist forces have prepared
the way by spreading dissention

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:51.610
and producing cleavages
among its people.

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:55.250
In counteracting such tactics,
especially in an emergency,

00:20:55.250 --> 00:20:58.810
there will be a tendency
towards cultural regimentation,

00:20:58.810 --> 00:21:01.960
and writing roughshod over
the emotions and sensibilities

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:05.800
of the nationality groups,
and immigrant populations.

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:09.490
An effective defense program
calls for national unity.

00:21:09.490 --> 00:21:11.450
But any effort towards
national unity

00:21:11.450 --> 00:21:16.750
that disregards cultural diversity,
will defeat its own ends."

00:21:16.750 --> 00:21:19.560
With this in mind, the Radio
Research Project responded

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:22.980
to the problem in one of its out
[inaudible], the Regional Series,

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:29.260
as follows, "In short, we show or
hope to show, the real significance

00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:33.010
of the big concept words such as
democracy, liberty, and America,

00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:36.280
by breaking them down into
their everyday manifestations

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:40.330
in communities or regions
throughout the country.

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:42.560
These programs do not
speak in generalities,

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:45.240
catch phrases, or glorious words.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:49.580
The stories are simply told
in dramatic and human terms,

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:52.440
sometimes through the eye of an
individual, be he a reverend,

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:56.770
and old sailor, a coal
miner, or even a river."

00:21:56.770 --> 00:21:58.990
In total, the Radio
Research Project,

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:02.420
resulted in six broadcasts
and two -- sorry.

00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:05.480
Six radio series and two
standalone broadcasts,

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:08.890 position:56%
included not only the folk music
and ballad hunting that we associate

00:22:08.890 --> 00:22:11.660 position:56%
with Lomax, but also, oral histories

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:14.520
and cultural memory drawn
from across the country.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:22.110
Lomax's promotion of national
unity through the medium of radio,

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:24.190
therefore not only took account of

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:27.140
but celebrated America's
internal diversity.

00:22:27.140 --> 00:22:30.820
And then we see these ideas
applied in an international setting

00:22:30.820 --> 00:22:34.190
in his work on Trans-Atlantic
Call: People to People,

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:37.060
which immediately followed
but was not a direct output

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:39.630
of the radio research project.

00:22:39.630 --> 00:22:42.620
Lomax was invited to work
on Trans-Atlantic Call

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:44.760 position:56%
by the Columbia Broadcasting System,

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:47.940
and the program was a collaborative
venture between the CBS and BVC,

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:51.660
which ran between 1943 to '45.

00:22:51.660 --> 00:22:55.940
And was explicitly designed to
foster a friendly appreciation

00:22:55.940 --> 00:22:57.880
and understanding between listeners

00:22:57.880 --> 00:23:01.520
in the United States
and the United Kingdom.

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:05.060
Initially conceived as alternating
half an hour broadcasts coming one

00:23:05.060 --> 00:23:08.160
week from the U.S., and the
next week from the U.K.,

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:11.900
Lomax and his team visited
communities across America,

00:23:11.900 --> 00:23:13.990
taking field notes,
making recordings,

00:23:13.990 --> 00:23:18.570
and interviewing local people
in order to capture the breadths

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:21.880
and depths of American
vernacular life.

00:23:21.880 --> 00:23:25.620
Throughout the broadcasts,
emphasized the impact of the war

00:23:25.620 --> 00:23:27.300
and the changes in life
that have been brought

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:30.400
to bear on everyday communities.

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:33.010
The broadcasts directly
addressed the British audience,

00:23:33.010 --> 00:23:35.350
explaining the industry's
terminologies

00:23:35.350 --> 00:23:38.360
and technologies evident
in each location.

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:40.910
One representative
episode featured Mason City

00:23:40.910 --> 00:23:43.060
in Iowa, a large farming city.

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:47.790
And Lomax's field notes, show
that he interviewed characters

00:23:47.790 --> 00:23:49.730
from a wide range of
ethnic backgrounds,

00:23:49.730 --> 00:23:53.910
including Irish farmers, Greek
canteen workers, and I also wanted

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:56.000 position:56%
to show this rather -- oop, hold on.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.940
Charming photograph, of Lomax
recording a flock of turkeys

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:02.830
that were eventually
broadcast in the program.

00:24:02.830 --> 00:24:07.090
And also, actually got into
conversation with Lomax

00:24:07.090 --> 00:24:10.110
and his interviewee at the time.

00:24:10.110 --> 00:24:13.590
So, Lomax's field notes
became scripts

00:24:13.590 --> 00:24:15.830
that were then voiced by actors.

00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:18.220
So, the scripts are fairly
expositionary [assumed spelling],

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:21.880
highlighting potential confusions
from Americans or British English.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:25.690
Explaining it out for example,
what Americans call corn,

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:28.500
the U.K. farmers would
call maize, pigs, the hogs,

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:32.330
explaining the differences between
English farms and America farms.

00:24:32.330 --> 00:24:35.060
And, so on.

00:24:35.060 --> 00:24:39.210
As part of his attempt to capture
the breadth of America's social

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:42.340
and cultural diversity,
Lomax also ensured

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:45.280
that American urban life was
represented alongside more

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:46.770
rural communities.

00:24:46.770 --> 00:24:50.340
And in one particular
broadcast from 1943,

00:24:50.340 --> 00:24:53.430
Lobal visits New York's Upper
East Side, and throughout,

00:24:53.430 --> 00:24:55.190
the emphasizes again the range

00:24:55.190 --> 00:24:59.140
of ethnic backgrounds living
alongside each other in harmony,

00:24:59.140 --> 00:25:03.550
with one character exclaiming,
"Italians, Jewish, Irish,

00:25:03.550 --> 00:25:05.210
Negroes, all the same here.

00:25:05.210 --> 00:25:08.680
My name's Coco, yours is
Cohen, yours is Fennesey.

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:12.910
We're all alike, 100% Americans."

00:25:12.910 --> 00:25:16.460
Later in the series the
format moved from actually --

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:20.070
from half an hour from one country
and then half an hour from another,

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:22.310
to actually switch to
broadcast halfway through,

00:25:22.310 --> 00:25:25.070
so there would be a
15-minute segment from America

00:25:25.070 --> 00:25:28.090
and then a reply immediately
with 15-minutes from the U.K.

00:25:28.090 --> 00:25:32.020
And unfortunately, we don't
have the reply from Soho

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:34.290
which would have replied
to the Upper East Side.

00:25:34.290 --> 00:25:36.450
But it would be fascinating
to see if

00:25:36.450 --> 00:25:40.530
and how the BBC reflected the
diversity of Central London

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:43.650
in a manner similar
to Lomax's conception.

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:49.600
However, we are able to listen
to one of the replying programs

00:25:49.600 --> 00:25:52.630
from the BBC, which
focused on the experience

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:54.880
of women in wartime Britain.

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:57.330
The narrator has just
been seen the morning

00:25:57.330 --> 00:26:00.150
after a bombing raid,
and we pick it up there.

00:26:00.150 --> 00:26:03.560
If we could have the audio?

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.510
&gt;&gt; There are a lot of
people standing around,

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:08.460
people who lost their homes, and
well, they were being advised

00:26:08.460 --> 00:26:10.690
by the women and the Women's
Voluntary Service, you know the--

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:12.040
&gt;&gt; Yes, yes, I know the WVS.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:13.600
&gt;&gt; Oh, yes, that's it.

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:15.980
Well, I went in to see if
there was anything I could do

00:26:15.980 --> 00:26:17.280
to help, I guess.

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:20.260
And standing in front of one
of the tables was an old lady.

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:22.740
I suppose she was about 60.

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:29.260
&gt;&gt; I'm sorry to be
troubling you like this.

00:26:29.260 --> 00:26:32.510
You must have a terrible lot to do.

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:34.080
&gt;&gt; We're here to help, Mrs. Brown.

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:35.600
That's our job.

00:26:35.600 --> 00:26:40.860
&gt;&gt; Well, you see, I -- I
lost everything last night.

00:26:40.860 --> 00:26:45.160
My house down, my husband,
they took him

00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:48.790
to hospital, but it wasn't any use.

00:26:48.790 --> 00:26:50.750
&gt;&gt; I'm terribly sorry, Mrs. Brown.

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:53.460 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I don't hardly know how to begin.

00:26:53.460 --> 00:26:58.430
I -- you see, I've
nowhere to go now.

00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:01.740
My girl was killed in
the Blitzen [phonetic].

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:03.210
I've no one I can go--

00:27:03.210 --> 00:27:05.320
&gt;&gt; We can take care of
that for you, Mrs. Brown.

00:27:05.320 --> 00:27:08.530
The rehousing people at the
Emergency Center will fix you up.

00:27:08.530 --> 00:27:09.830
&gt;&gt; Oh thank you, miss.

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:11.800
I don't know where it is.

00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:13.240
I thought perhaps you might--

00:27:13.240 --> 00:27:15.470
&gt;&gt; One of us will take
you around there.

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:17.980
And we'll call the
Assistance Board as well.

00:27:17.980 --> 00:27:21.270
If your house is gone, there's
a lot of things you'll need,

00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:23.670
money and clothes and
food and things.

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:25.600
&gt;&gt; That's very kind of you, miss.

00:27:25.600 --> 00:27:29.500
I don't want to be any trouble.

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:34.100
I'm sure that there must
be lots worse off than me.

00:27:34.100 --> 00:27:37.760
&gt;&gt; I don't think anyone could lose
more than you've lost, Mrs. Brown.

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:40.340
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Kate Neale: So,

00:27:40.340 --> 00:27:42.580
these returning broadcasts explored
aspects and impacts of the war

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:45.170
in Britain that were outside
the realms of experience

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:47.290
for your average American citizen,

00:27:47.290 --> 00:27:51.100
often in very dramatic
and poignant terms.

00:27:51.100 --> 00:27:53.910
So, Trans-Atlantic Call
and Radio Research Project,

00:27:53.910 --> 00:27:57.640
both intended to build [inaudible]
communities with particular social

00:27:57.640 --> 00:28:00.930
and political goals in mind,
fostering cultural dialogs

00:28:00.930 --> 00:28:03.600
at both sub and international
levels.

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:05.690
The Library of Congress's
holdings relating

00:28:05.690 --> 00:28:09.370 position:56%
to the Radio Research Project and
Trans-Atlantic Call itself, are rich

00:28:09.370 --> 00:28:12.470
and broad and include
Lomax's original field notes,

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:16.360
correspondence, institutional
policy reports and documentation,

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:19.920
as well as the radio scripts
and audio files themselves.

00:28:19.920 --> 00:28:22.810
And as an ethnomusicologist,
I'm fascinated by the use

00:28:22.810 --> 00:28:26.820 position:56%
of musical material in culture, in
these projects, to build communities

00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.490
and develop particular
narratives around them.

00:28:29.490 --> 00:28:31.900
And there are many interesting
strands to be drawn out.

00:28:31.900 --> 00:28:35.610
In particular, how Lomax'
description so much gives a voice

00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:38.460
to the voiceless perhaps,
but script the voiceless,

00:28:38.460 --> 00:28:42.000 position:56%
because these scripts were carefully
constructed, curated, and of course,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:46.810
eventually approved for broadcast
by the Office of War Information.

00:28:46.810 --> 00:28:49.490
However, the material begs
attention from a wide field

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:50.790
of academic disciplines

00:28:50.790 --> 00:28:54.290
since Lomax's radio work offers
fertile ground for the exploration

00:28:54.290 --> 00:28:57.640
and intersection of media
and institutional approaches

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:00.930
to folk like, the construction
and delivery of propaganda,

00:29:00.930 --> 00:29:04.840
and the inclusions and the
exclusions of marginalized groups,

00:29:04.840 --> 00:29:07.940
all of which concern
us in the present day.

00:29:07.940 --> 00:29:09.740
Thank you very much.

00:29:09.740 --> 00:29:17.860
