00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:04.140
This was the BBC's Arts
and Culture Station,

00:33:04.140 --> 00:33:05.970
formed after the Second World War,

00:33:05.970 --> 00:33:08.050
to complement the corporations
of the networks.

00:33:08.050 --> 00:33:11.490
The Home Service, which was current
affairs, and the Light Program,

00:33:11.490 --> 00:33:13.860
which was mainly for music
and variety entertainment.

00:33:13.860 --> 00:33:17.940
And the station's approach, the
Third Program's station's approach,

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:20.640
was firmly highbrow
and intellectual.

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:24.090
The first evening of transmission
began with a lecture on how

00:33:24.090 --> 00:33:27.170
to listen, and it included
recordings of Bach's

00:33:27.170 --> 00:33:30.360
"Goldbergs Variations,"
Monteverdi's "Madrigals," a lecture

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:33.100
on current affairs by the
Prime Minister of South Africa,

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:35.060
and a concert with
English composers,

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:36.780
[inaudible] from the
BBC Symphony Hall.

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:42.110
What the station did on select
occasions, widen its remit

00:33:42.110 --> 00:33:43.410
to the subject of folksong,

00:33:43.410 --> 00:33:46.700
particularly if the presenter
was a well-regarded authority

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:48.000
on the subject.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.730
And Alan Lomax was
certainly recognized as such,

00:33:50.730 --> 00:33:52.030
by the station's controllers.

00:33:52.030 --> 00:33:56.530
So, the Art of the Negro is a
short series, compared to some

00:33:56.530 --> 00:33:58.890
of Lomax's other radio projects,

00:33:58.890 --> 00:34:01.710
running to only three
hour-long episodes.

00:34:01.710 --> 00:34:04.390
These are Mr. Jelly Roll,
about the jazz composer

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:08.070
and pianist Jelly Roll Morton and
the birth of jazz in New Orleans,

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:11.240
Trumpets of the Lord, about
African-American religious worship,

00:34:11.240 --> 00:34:14.290
and then finally Blues
in the Mississippi Night,

00:34:14.290 --> 00:34:18.960
about the origins, themes, and
social meanings of the blues.

00:34:18.960 --> 00:34:21.230
The AFC's holdings
on these broadcasts,

00:34:21.230 --> 00:34:24.810
are limited to a set
of finished scripts.

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:27.660
However, these are
exceptionally rich documents.

00:34:27.660 --> 00:34:29.610
They reveal how Lomax
constructed each episode

00:34:29.610 --> 00:34:32.210
from a wide range of audio sources.

00:34:32.210 --> 00:34:34.730
Lomax drew from across
his own earlier fieldwork

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:37.950
and musical knowledge, including
recordings made while working

00:34:37.950 --> 00:34:41.340
for the Archive of American Folk
Song, more recent interviews

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:44.110
that he had conducted with
folk singers and musicians,

00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:46.890
and then commercial
recordings of blues and jazz.

00:34:46.890 --> 00:34:49.670
And without wanting to
go into too much detail,

00:34:49.670 --> 00:34:52.420
it's possible to use the
holdings of the Lomax collection,

00:34:52.420 --> 00:34:56.720
to dig right down into
this process of authorship.

00:34:56.720 --> 00:35:01.100
This slip for example, show
Lomax using the BBC's in-house

00:35:01.100 --> 00:35:04.930 position:56%
reproduction services to make copies
of interview materials he'd brought

00:35:04.930 --> 00:35:07.460
with him in preparation
for the broadcast.

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:11.110
And then correspondence files
show the BBC and the Library

00:35:11.110 --> 00:35:14.700
of Congress already had a
well-established exchange program,

00:35:14.700 --> 00:35:17.650
meaning that many of Lomax's
earliest field recordings,

00:35:17.650 --> 00:35:22.950
were actually already over at the
BBC and in their record library.

00:35:22.950 --> 00:35:28.130
Lomax [inaudible] source approach,
was integral to his belief

00:35:28.130 --> 00:35:31.520 position:56%
that folk song or folk culture was
a bedrock of American popular music.

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:36.120
In Blues in the Mississippi Night,
Lomax begins by casting the blues

00:35:36.120 --> 00:35:39.180
as the musical voice
of a modern nation.

00:35:39.180 --> 00:35:40.990
"The term 'the blues'
is old," he says.

00:35:40.990 --> 00:35:42.520
"Shakespeare used it.

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:44.430
The song form, is like
the Cante jondo

00:35:44.430 --> 00:35:46.520
of Spain, the Fado of Portugal.

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:51.090
All three are routed in Africa,
but the blues is the folk song

00:35:51.090 --> 00:35:55.890
of the 20th Century, at home with
machinery, and on city streets.

00:35:55.890 --> 00:36:01.510
If America had one national
song, it's probably-- ."

00:36:01.510 --> 00:36:09.140
[ Music ]

00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:11.750 position:56%
Can we play that from the beginning?

00:36:11.750 --> 00:36:14.730
I'll do my radio intro again.

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:16.530
Or Lomax's radio intro.

00:36:16.530 --> 00:36:34.700
[ Music ]

00:36:34.700 --> 00:36:39.400 position:56%
National music then, to Lomax's
ears, was music created and consumed

00:36:39.400 --> 00:36:42.460
by the people, within
their everyday lives.

00:36:42.460 --> 00:36:45.540
This is evident in Lomax's
recollection of his first encounter

00:36:45.540 --> 00:36:48.000
with the blue's musician,
McKinley Morganfield,

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:49.670
better known now as Muddy Waters.

00:36:49.670 --> 00:36:52.230
And he recorded, while
collecting songs

00:36:52.230 --> 00:36:56.840
in the Mississippi delta
during the summer of 1941.

00:36:56.840 --> 00:36:59.490
"He was barefooted
in ragged overalls.

00:36:59.490 --> 00:37:02.970
His house, in the middle of one
of those endless cornfields.

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:06.550
He played every Saturday for
little dances in his county,

00:37:06.550 --> 00:37:10.090
but he had never seen a good
guitar before he picked up mine.

00:37:10.090 --> 00:37:12.140
But listen to his song.

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:15.930
A complex, delicately
balanced, syncopated poem,

00:37:15.930 --> 00:37:19.510 position:56%
perhaps the finest blues on record."

00:37:19.510 --> 00:37:55.950
[ Music ]

00:37:55.950 --> 00:37:58.850
So here, Lomax is again
turning conventional opinion

00:37:58.850 --> 00:38:01.340
about musical value on its head.

00:38:01.340 --> 00:38:05.260
Even those who were confined to the
bottom rungs of American society,

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:07.870
with few material resources
and little formal education,

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:12.520
could produce music with immense
artistic value and beauty.

00:38:12.520 --> 00:38:14.710
For British listeners
of the Third Program,

00:38:14.710 --> 00:38:17.130
this would have been
a powerful image.

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:20.580 position:56%
While they could access commercial
blues recordings with relative ease,

00:38:20.580 --> 00:38:23.390
they lacked any real awareness
of the music's folk roots,

00:38:23.390 --> 00:38:25.620
or the environment in
which it was created.

00:38:25.620 --> 00:38:28.980
And this is the real
emphasis of this social --

00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:33.550
emphasis on social context
rather, it's the real centerpiece

00:38:33.550 --> 00:38:36.630 position:56%
of Lomax's broadcasts here, I think.

00:38:36.630 --> 00:38:39.320
Lomax draws on a series of
interviews with blues musicians,

00:38:39.320 --> 00:38:42.210
Big Bill Broonzy, Memphis
Slim, and Sonny Boy Williamson,

00:38:42.210 --> 00:38:44.680
that he had made in
New York in 1947.

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:47.530
But they are presented
here as taking place

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:50.390
in a back-country Mississippi
juke joint.

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:51.860
"The night settled down.

00:38:51.860 --> 00:38:54.220
One of those hot, [inaudible]
August nights

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:55.520
in the Mississippi [inaudible].

00:38:55.520 --> 00:38:58.450
The blues was rolling
slow, sleepy, and tired.

00:38:58.450 --> 00:39:00.650
It was time to ask questions.

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:02.190
I said, 'Listen, Bill.

00:39:02.190 --> 00:39:03.950
You sit here and sing
the blues all night,

00:39:03.950 --> 00:39:05.330 position:56%
and never seem to get tired of them.

00:39:05.330 --> 00:39:07.570
What are they about anyway?'"

00:39:07.570 --> 00:39:14.920
&gt;&gt; Some people say that
the blues is a [inaudible],

00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:16.910
but I don't say it like that.

00:39:16.910 --> 00:39:20.340
I say it's a man that's got a
companion and she turned him down.

00:39:20.340 --> 00:39:23.520
And things like that
happen, you know?

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:25.350
And that's why I gets
the blues from.

00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:29.530
When I want to see my baby,
and want to see her bad,

00:39:29.530 --> 00:39:32.060
and something happened
and I can't find her,

00:39:32.060 --> 00:39:34.400
and that gives me the blues.,

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:37.340
&gt;&gt; Lawrence Davies: So, although
Lomax's setting is fictionalized,

00:39:37.340 --> 00:39:41.150
the musicians' testimony was
direct and from the heart.

00:39:41.150 --> 00:39:44.880 position:56%
Speaking under pseudonyms to protect
their identities, Broonzy, Slim,

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:48.180
and Williamson, spoke candidly
about their experiences

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:51.660
of crushing manual labor, harsh
treatment by white bosses,

00:39:51.660 --> 00:39:53.820
and how the blues could be used

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:57.650
to voice the trauma
of these experiences.

00:39:57.650 --> 00:40:01.890 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I've known guys, they wanted to
cuss out the boss, and he was afraid

00:40:01.890 --> 00:40:04.290
to go up to his face and tell
him what he wanted to tell him.

00:40:04.290 --> 00:40:07.240
And I've heard him say sing
those things, sing words,

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:09.130
you know, back to the boss.

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:12.870 position:56%
Just be behind the wagon, hooking
up the horses or something, and then

00:40:12.870 --> 00:40:14.170
or the mules of something.

00:40:14.170 --> 00:40:15.940
And then he'd go to
work and go to singing,

00:40:15.940 --> 00:40:19.150
and said things to
the horse, you know?

00:40:19.150 --> 00:40:21.150
Horse [inaudible] like the
mule, stepped on his foot.

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:23.630
Said, "Get off my foot, God damn
it," or something like that.

00:40:23.630 --> 00:40:26.530
You know? And he meant he
was talking to the boss,

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:30.180 position:56%
"Son of a bitch, [inaudible] get off
my foot," and such things as that.

00:40:30.180 --> 00:40:31.480
That's the point.

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:34.000
&gt;&gt; Yes, blues is kind of
a revenge, you know it-- ?

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.510
&gt;&gt; Lawrence Davies: So, these
accounts laid bare the evils

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:40.000
of segregation, but also the
optimism and resourcefulness

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.920
of spirit that helped
people survive.

00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:45.320
Such as this apocryphal
yet sinister tale

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.360
of a delta farm owner
named Mr. White.

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:51.660
&gt;&gt; I know a man at my home.

00:40:51.660 --> 00:40:54.720
They call him Mr. White.

00:40:54.720 --> 00:40:56.020
That was at on the plantation.

00:40:56.020 --> 00:40:57.320
Well, he had his own place there.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:00.230
It was about 50 or 60
miles of his place.

00:41:00.230 --> 00:41:01.730 position:56%
It's a square, you know what I mean?

00:41:01.730 --> 00:41:04.450
From one side to another, you know?

00:41:04.450 --> 00:41:08.230
And all his fences around
his place was white.

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:11.720
The trees, he painted them white
up as far as you could get.

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:17.240
And all the cattle and the sheeps,
the goats, and the hogs, and cows

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:19.680
and mules, horses, and
everything on his place was white.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:25.540 position:56%
And anytime that his cow or his goat
or [inaudible] have a black goat

00:41:25.540 --> 00:41:30.110
or a black sheep or a black calf,
a black colt, anything like that,

00:41:30.110 --> 00:41:31.690
he give them to the niggers.

00:41:31.690 --> 00:41:35.430
He didn't want nothing
on his plantation black.

00:41:35.430 --> 00:41:37.250
&gt;&gt; Lawrence Davies: To be
able to hear such lengthy

00:41:37.250 --> 00:41:41.100
and personal accounts of life
in the south and in such detail,

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:44.680
was unprecedented, not only in
Britain, but in blues scholarship

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:47.290
as a whole in this period.

00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:48.970
These broadcasts were
therefore an early step

00:41:48.970 --> 00:41:51.460
in understanding the unique
circumstances that gave rise

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:54.950
to African-American
traditional music, and how Black

00:41:54.950 --> 00:42:00.110
and expressive culture inspired
American popular music as a whole.

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:02.440
Moreover, we can trace
from this one broadcast,

00:42:02.440 --> 00:42:06.480
how Lomax continually reused and
reformulated the field recordings

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:08.760
and interview materials
that he used in the Art

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:11.760
of the Negro throughout his career.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:14.960 position:56%
His interviews with African-American
musicians became the inspiration

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:20.320
for several books, LPs, and
even a documentary film.

00:42:20.320 --> 00:42:25.050
Lomax clearly heard great
power in these recordings,

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:29.020
and I think we can hear that same
power when we listen to them today.

00:42:29.020 --> 00:42:32.140
In this way, the future engagement
with Lomax's radio materials

00:42:32.140 --> 00:42:34.710
that his project aims to inspire,

00:42:34.710 --> 00:42:37.420
will hopefully allow
the important messages

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:41.030
of the AFC's collections
to continue to be heard.

00:42:41.030 --> 00:42:42.830
Thank you.

00:42:42.830 --> 00:42:50.820
[ Applause ]

00:42:50.820 --> 00:42:56.510
If I could now hand over to my
colleague, Dr. Delaina Sepko.

00:42:56.510 --> 00:43:03.710
[ Applause ]

00:43:03.710 --> 00:43:06.390
&gt;&gt; Dr. Delaina Sepko: I'm just
going to switch it up a wee bit.

00:43:06.390 --> 00:43:09.670
Stand here if that's alright
so I can see the slides.

00:43:09.670 --> 00:43:11.840
Thank you very much for
joining us this afternoon.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:13.910
It really means a lot
to us to have you hear.

00:43:13.910 --> 00:43:19.510
And could we have the
first sound clip, please?

00:43:19.510 --> 00:43:35.700
[ Music ]

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:38.060
&gt;&gt; Alan Lomax: Get on board
everybody, and ride with me.

00:43:38.060 --> 00:43:40.490 position:56%
This is Alan Lomax, your ballad man,

00:43:40.490 --> 00:43:42.950
inviting you for another
ride on the Folk Song Train.

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:47.510
The train that runs wherever
the people make their music.

00:43:47.510 --> 00:44:00.090
[ Music ]

00:44:00.090 --> 00:44:01.390
&gt;&gt; Dr. Delaina Sepko: Thank you.

00:44:01.390 --> 00:44:05.740
I'm here to just introduce you
a little bit to another one

00:44:05.740 --> 00:44:07.040
of his radio broadcasts, called the

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:10.860
"The Ballad Man" or
"Your Ballad Man."

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:14.590
And to a particular episode
called, "Singing Newspaper."

00:44:14.590 --> 00:44:19.960
Now, the broadcast took place
on the 17th of July, 1948.

00:44:19.960 --> 00:44:21.910
And it was one of 60
episodes that aired

00:44:21.910 --> 00:44:27.200
between October 1947
and January 1949.

00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:30.900
In terms of construction, there
were two 15-mintues halves,

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:34.550
with a total of 30 minutes,
and the broadcast took place

00:44:34.550 --> 00:44:37.880
on Mutual Broadcasting Network,
which could be considered one

00:44:37.880 --> 00:44:42.370
of the four major broadcasters
of that time.

00:44:42.370 --> 00:44:44.000
They were topical in nature.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:47.370
So, when they were put together,
they might be about women and men.

00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:50.510
In this case, it's
about popular topics

00:44:50.510 --> 00:44:55.040
that you might find in a newspaper.

00:44:55.040 --> 00:44:59.890
This particular episode, which
I have here the playlist for,

00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:04.430
shows that it's generally
composed of recorded music,

00:45:04.430 --> 00:45:08.720
some live performances,
and Lomax gives commentary

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:10.530
over the top of most of it.

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.980
So, it might be what
you would find familiar

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:16.370
from today's radio broadcasts.

00:45:16.370 --> 00:45:18.550
So, in that respect,
it has a very sort

00:45:18.550 --> 00:45:21.260
of dee-jay sort of approach to it.

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:25.820
However, this playlist is
entirely made-up of prerecorded,

00:45:25.820 --> 00:45:28.100
commercially recorded music.

00:45:28.100 --> 00:45:35.690
What we can see from that is
that we've got a combination

00:45:35.690 --> 00:45:39.240
of live performance and recorded
music that's happening during each

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:44.820
of these broadcasts, and what
we can see, although I'd hoped

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:47.100
that was a little bit bigger there,

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:52.460
what we have is a request
for reissue, basically.

00:45:52.460 --> 00:45:55.900
So, what was happening is the
broadcast would play a song,

00:45:55.900 --> 00:45:57.200
people would write in, in the way

00:45:57.200 --> 00:46:00.090
that my colleagues been already
telling you about, asking,

00:46:00.090 --> 00:46:01.930
"Where can I buy that record?

00:46:01.930 --> 00:46:03.280
Where can I get that song?"

00:46:03.280 --> 00:46:06.820
Well, a lot of them were really
difficult to get your hands on.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:10.330
So, here we can see
a demand for reissue.

00:46:10.330 --> 00:46:12.550
People are wanting copies.

00:46:12.550 --> 00:46:17.790
Copies that are commercially
produced, in this case.

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:19.580
Now, anybody who's familiar
with commercial music,

00:46:19.580 --> 00:46:22.290
knows that there a few hoops that
you need to jump through in order

00:46:22.290 --> 00:46:25.080
to be able to play them, and
this was the case even back then.

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:29.750 position:56%
So, here we can see a list
including some of the songs that are

00:46:29.750 --> 00:46:36.210
on this particular episode, asking
for those tracks to be cleared.

00:46:36.210 --> 00:46:40.790
Meaning, given permission
to play them on the radio.

00:46:40.790 --> 00:46:45.380
So, what we're starting to see
in this case, is a little bit

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:50.070 position:56%
of tension between folk music,
which is generally seen as something

00:46:50.070 --> 00:46:53.990
that you share, that
you do as a community,

00:46:53.990 --> 00:46:57.230
and that's something that's very
much part of American cultures

00:46:57.230 --> 00:47:01.360
in that respect, versus,
commercial recordings,

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:05.670
things that are commodified and
require permission for broadcast.

00:47:05.670 --> 00:47:12.490
However, Lomax still incorporates
a lot of the traditional formats

00:47:12.490 --> 00:47:16.300
that he's been using in all the
other broadcasts where he's asking

00:47:16.300 --> 00:47:18.810
for input, looking for
feedback from people,

00:47:18.810 --> 00:47:21.720
and really wanting an exchange.

00:47:21.720 --> 00:47:24.980
The sort of recursive
format, a back and forth.

00:47:24.980 --> 00:47:27.900
Something that is reflective
of the folk communities

00:47:27.900 --> 00:47:31.350
that he works for and with.

00:47:31.350 --> 00:47:35.810
And in this respect, you could
sort of see these broadcasts

00:47:35.810 --> 00:47:39.700
as [inaudible] a conduit
for folk music

00:47:39.700 --> 00:47:42.630
and folk cultures that
they're part of.

00:47:42.630 --> 00:47:47.370
So, in this case, we
have a letter, and --

00:47:47.370 --> 00:47:50.210
that he's written to
somebody who sent stuff in.

00:47:50.210 --> 00:47:53.650
And it's just an expression
of gratitude.

00:47:53.650 --> 00:47:55.870
I hope that he can get
it into his broadcast,

00:47:55.870 --> 00:47:59.440
but that he's only got eight songs
that he can play per episode,

00:47:59.440 --> 00:48:01.630
it might take him a
little while to get to it.

00:48:01.630 --> 00:48:07.630 position:56%
And then the other image is in
fact, a list to honor those requests

00:48:07.630 --> 00:48:10.470
that came through,
a list of requests

00:48:10.470 --> 00:48:12.720
that have been made from fan mail.

